    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get the basic idea of the pressure difference but the \"faster air\" thing always felt a bit hand-wavy to me. why *must* it go faster over the top? is there something about the air itself or the way it's forced to move that causes that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I understand where you're coming from. The \"faster air\" part might seem a bit mysterious, but it's actually rooted in the principles of fluid dynamics. When the wing moves through the air, it essentially forces the air to move over and around it. Because the wing's upper surface is curved, it has to cover a longer distance in the same amount of time compared to the flatter bottom surface. This is similar to how a water wheel turns faster when the water flows over its curved surface compared to a flat one.\n\nSo, the air has to speed up over the top surface to \"keep up\" with the wing's movement, just like how a water wheel spins faster when the water flows over it. This increased speed over the top surface leads to lower pressure, which creates the lift that helps the wing (and the plane) stay in the air. It's a bit like how a gust of wind can pick up speed when it encounters a hill, causing it to blow more strongly over the top of the hill. The faster-moving air over the wing's top surface results in a lower pressure, which is what allows the wing to lift off the ground.",
