    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense, but that \"longer distance\" explanation is sometimes criticized as being the \"equal transit time\" fallacy, right? like air doesn't actually have to travel the same time to reach the end. can u explain the role of flow turning or the Coanda effect instead? how does the air actually get \"bent\" by the wing shape?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you're right! The \"equal transit time\" explanation can indeed be a bit misleading. Air doesn't have to reach the end at the same time, but it's more about the air being \"forced\" to move faster over the curved top surface of the wing due to the wing's shape and the way it moves through the air.\n\nNow, let's talk about the Coanda effect. The Coanda effect is a phenomenon where a fluid (in this case, air) tends to stick to a curved surface and follow its contour. When the wing moves through the air, the air molecules near the wing's surface are pushed outwards due to the wing's curvature. These molecules then tend to follow the curved surface of the wing, creating a smooth, attached flow over the wing's top surface.\n\nThis attached flow of air over the wing's top surface helps to maintain the faster speed of the air, which in turn creates the lower pressure needed for lift. It's like how a stream of water flowing over a curved surface will tend to stick to the surface and follow its contour. The Coanda effect helps to keep the air flowing smoothly over the wing, which is crucial for generating lift.\n\nSo, the wing's shape and the Coanda effect work together",
      "source": "target",
      "gen_token_ids": [
